                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>JEREMIAH PILCHER. I am a colourman. In 1799 I lived in Tooley-street. I bought some window lead of Messrs. Day and Roberts. On the 1st of February the prisoner called; I paid him eight pounds five shillings, and he gave me a receipt.</p>
               <p>Mr. Day. The prisoner never accounted for that money. He left our service in 1805. I have not known where he was since.</p>
               <p>Mr. Arabin. Did not you know this young man had a house in Russell-street, Bloomsbury - A. His wife lived there. I did not know where he lived. I understood he was an nsher at a school.</p>
               <p>Q. Why did not you prefer the bill before - A. I should have thought he would have come and paid it.</p>

               <p>The prisoner left his defence to his counsel. Called five witnesses, who gave him a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18120916-192-verdict1042" type="verdictDescription">
